<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1890-08-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1890-08-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="69" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d69">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Mizner</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1890-08-19"><hi rend="italic">August</hi> 19,
                            1890</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 155.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 126 of the 28th
                        ultimo, acknowledging the receipt on the 23d ultimo, through Mr. Ryan, of
                        the Department’s telegram of the 19th of the same month, relating to the
                        seizure by the Guatemalan Government of the arms on board the steamship <hi rend="italic">Colima.</hi></p>
                    <p>Consideration of this subject is necessarily deferred until your further
                        dispatches shall place the whole case before the Department and the action
                        of the Gutemalan Government upon your demands in respect to this
                        unjustifiable seizure shall be known.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">William F. Wharton.</hi><lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>